Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.99,0:00:07.71,Default,,0,0,0,,The most crucial moment in life is during decision making.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.25,0:00:13.83,Default,,0,0,0,,The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.33,0:00:19.97,Default,,0,0,0,,But also instilled numerous lessons on how to live.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.37,0:00:31.39,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(100,700)\c&H0007DF&\fs100\b1\bord0\blur1}Animentary\N{\b\c&HE0DBF3&}Decision
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.57,0:00:43.33,Default,,0,0,30,,Wit is your weapon \NRemember to use your head {智恵をめぐらせ 頭を使え}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.33,0:00:50.95,Default,,0,0,30,,Repress your anguish, \NIf you are a man{悩み抜け抜け 男なら}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.95,0:00:59.26,Default,,0,0,30,,One decision is enough \NTo make others cry or laugh{泣くも笑うも 決断ひとつ}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:59.26,0:01:06.69,Default,,0,0,30,,If you win, don't hold your head high, \NIf you lose, don't cry{勝っておごるな 敗れて泣くな}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.69,0:01:14.55,Default,,0,0,30,,Men, don't you ever let others see your tears{男 涙は見せぬもの}
Comment: 0,0:01:34.91,0:01:34.95,Default,,0,0,0,,{ch}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:41.95,0:01:48.02,Sign,,0,0,260,,{\c&HE3F3EC&\fade(500,0)\b1\blur1\bord1\3c&HABB3A4&}Episode 25 \N{\fs130}The Final Decision
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.02,0:01:50.02,Default,,0,0,0,,On the morning of April 27th,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:50.02,0:01:54.53,Default,,0,0,0,,a trilateral joint declaration \Nfrom the UK, the US, and China was announced.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.07,0:01:57.51,Default,,0,0,0,,The Potsdam Declaration that Japan received last night.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:58.28,0:02:05.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, this morning, the head of the intelligence bureau \Nfrom Suzuki Kantaro's cabinet, Shimomura Hiroshi
Dialogue: 0,0:02:05.58,0:02:12.62,Default,,0,0,0,,was admiring the tenacity of a small bird, who never ceased \Nto forage for food even amidst these ravaged lands. {lit: strength/indomitability of coming to look for food in the scorched earth - no clue what's there to admire and what we're seeing doesn't seem like scorched earth either, it was never executed on japanese mainland}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.62,0:02:13.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Good morning, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.09,0:02:16.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Is that you, Oyadomari? Good morning. {https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E8%A6%AA%E6%B3%8A%E6%9C%9D%E7%9C%81#%E6%AF%94%E5%B3%B6%E6%B1%BA%E6%88%A6%E3%81%AE%E6%AD%8C}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:16.44,0:02:18.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. Important news, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:19.42,0:02:21.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Important news?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:21.08,0:02:27.83,Default,,0,0,0,,At 6 this morning, a tripartite declaration \Nby the US, UK and China arrived from San Francisco.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.83,0:02:31.64,Default,,0,0,0,,The US, UK, and China? \NAre you sure it's not US, UK, and the Soviets?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:31.64,0:02:33.58,Default,,0,0,0,,It's US, UK, and China, sir. Confirmed.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.61,0:02:35.36,Default,,0,0,0,,And what's in it?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:35.36,0:02:38.35,Default,,0,0,0,,A demand for our unconditional surrender.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:41.66,0:02:43.35,Default,,0,0,0,,It has 13 points in it. {only 9 in english version}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.87,0:02:50.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Most of it aligns with the previous Cairo Declaration.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.22,0:02:56.63,Default,,0,0,0,,That's true. What are your thoughts on it? \NNot as an intelligence officer, but as an individual.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.63,0:03:01.19,Default,,0,0,0,,As an individual, I see it in the same light \Nas a military intelligence officer.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:01.19,0:03:02.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:02.94,0:03:04.62,Default,,0,0,0,,We cannot accept it. {mokusatsu = [we should] ignore/disregard/shrug off/sweep under the rug; interestingly, here's a piece of history: This word ` ` mokusatsu '' was translated into English as ``ignore'' by Japan's national news agency, the Alliance News Agency , and was translated into English as ``reject'' by Reuters and the Associated Press .}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.62,0:03:07.30,Default,,0,0,0,,I wouldn't be so sure of that.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:07.30,0:03:08.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:25.20,0:03:27.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Upon a closer look,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.08,0:03:30.24,Default,,0,0,0,,this declaration is very harsh \Non our top brass militarists, {lit: war leaders}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:30.24,0:03:33.81,Default,,0,0,0,,but it offers the common people \Nmore civil liberties than they currently have.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.81,0:03:35.82,Default,,0,0,0,,It's just one big ploy.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:35.82,0:03:40.59,Default,,0,0,0,,They're calling for immediate surrender. \NI'm inclined to see it as our chance.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.59,0:03:42.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Surrendering to the US, UK, and China?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:42.57,0:03:44.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Correct.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:44.02,0:03:49.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Among our military top brass, there's no one in sight \Ncourageous enough to accept this demand for surrender.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.52,0:03:54.00,Default,,0,0,0,,They don't seem to understand \Nthat we no longer have any other options.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.50,0:04:00.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Our military is stalwartly bellicose, and the cabinet \Nis just trying its best to pass the blame.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.11,0:04:02.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Meanwhile, our chances are dwindling.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:02.53,0:04:06.98,Default,,0,0,0,,No. It's not just about our chances. \NIt's about preserving countless civilian lives.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:08.88,0:04:15.77,Default,,0,0,0,,The United States also informed Japan's populace of that \Nby distributing leaflets along with bombs.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:19.88,0:04:21.88,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\c&H323B99&\3c&HE9E9F0&\bord3\blur1}Military Police {憲}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:22.92,0:04:23.66,Sign,,0,0,0,,{unintelligible}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.11,0:04:41.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, the cabinet decided to portray the declaration \Nas a plot to cause civilian unrest.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.49,0:04:47.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Later, they decided to shrug off the declaration for now, \Npresuming it to be an underhanded attempt by the US
Dialogue: 0,0:04:47.52,0:04:49.58,Default,,0,0,0,,to force Japan to capitulate hastily. {meaning: "if we wait out for a bit longer, they'll present us with milder conditions"}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.44,0:04:58.23,Default,,0,0,0,,However, isn't this problem too well-known \Nto try and shrug off?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.23,0:05:04.34,Default,,0,0,0,,I believe, pretending we know nothing of this crucial issue in the morning newspapers will only arouse more suspicion. {unsure: この重大なニュースを知らん顔して新聞に載せるということはかえって疑惑を招くと存じます ; historically it was "Remaining silent is prudent; the news media should be instructed to print it without any comments."}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.34,0:05:07.82,Default,,0,0,0,,If most of the ministers \Nalso share this view, I shall respect it. {no clue what he means by 士官大臣 / officer minister, likely he means just shimomura himself}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.82,0:05:13.73,Default,,0,0,0,,But if we were to acknowledge it, \NI would only accept it in a decisively condemning light.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.73,0:05:18.33,Default,,0,0,0,,We can't afford a decline in morale. \NA boost to the fighting spirit is what we need now!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.33,0:05:24.34,Default,,0,0,0,,But if we do that, our current efforts to negotiate a peace \Nthrough the Soviet diplomats will come to nothing.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:24.34,0:05:27.85,Default,,0,0,0,,What? You're still trying to negotiate a peace?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:29.85,0:05:33.86,Default,,0,0,0,,We can't hope for a reasonable peace \Nif we don't show them our willingness to fight back!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.91,0:05:41.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Notwithstanding the fact that the Soviet representative \Nalso attended the Potsdam Conference,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.04,0:05:45.75,Default,,0,0,0,,the Japanese government was still hoping to conclude a conditional peace through the Soviet diplomats.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.75,0:05:49.51,Default,,0,0,0,,There were also talks about dispatching \NKonoe Fumimaro to Moscow as a liaison. {wiki: On June 22nd, Emperor Showa approved the government's decision to carry out ``peace negotiations mediated by the Soviet Union,'' which had been proposed by Minister of the Interior Koichi Kido and others, and on July 7th, he announced that ``it would be better to take the plunge and send a special envoy.'' '' he told Prime Minister Kantaro Suzuki . In response, Foreign Minister Shigenori Togo asked Konoe to serve as a special envoy, and on July 12, Konoe was officially appointed as a special envoy by the Emperor. At this time, Konoe replied, ``If you give me an order, I will risk my life.'' However, Konoe himself believed that Britain was the best place to mediate peace, and Morisada Hosokawa, a close aide , said, ``Mr. Konoe didn't like it.Well, but there's nothing we can do about it.His Majesty said so.'' So I was really reluctant to go to Moscow,'' he said after the war . [22] However, Konoe's dispatch to Moscow was effectively rejected by Stalin , who had decided to join the war against Japan at the Yalta Conference in February . }
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.21,0:05:58.04,Default,,0,0,0,,The US intelligence department chief \NCaptain Harry Cunningham declared this: {I absolutely couldn't find any traces of any such man}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:58.04,0:06:02.42,Default,,0,0,0,,"Japan's entire population \Nhas been effectively put on the front lines. {lit: became a first-class military target for the army}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:02.42,0:06:06.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Presently, there are no non-combatants in Japan.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.09,0:06:12.63,Default,,0,0,0,,It is now a battle of annihilating as many enemies as we can, men and women alike, in the shortest term possible." {unsure if quote ends here or on the next line}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.63,0:06:14.20,Default,,0,0,0,,While that's how they see it,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.87,0:06:19.28,Default,,0,0,0,,the people of Japan are still kept in the dark \Nabout the actual situation.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.28,0:06:21.73,Default,,0,0,0,,I think it's time for us to let them know.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.73,0:06:26.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Should any of you have any reason to oppose that, \Nbesides your personal disapproval,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.98,0:06:29.95,Default,,0,0,0,,I'd like you to let me know it openly.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:29.95,0:06:32.21,Default,,0,0,0,,It's the people who are bearing the main brunt. {lit: because people are in trouble/suffering}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.21,0:06:35.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Minister! What is that "bearing the brunt" bull?!
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.30,0:06:37.20,Default,,0,0,0,,The people are ecstatic to die. {/dying with happiness}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:37.20,0:06:38.71,Default,,0,0,0,,That's absurd!
Dialogue: 0,0:06:38.71,0:06:42.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Because you're just a civilian, \Nyou've no notion of true patriotism! {lit: have no feeling to worry about; to be anxious about; to be concerned about about the country}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:43.44,0:06:46.29,Default,,0,0,0,,I can by no means work under you! Excuse me!
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.12,0:06:55.81,Default,,0,0,0,,We really are in trouble.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.23,0:06:58.66,Default,,0,0,0,,There's much more to our troubles than this.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.21,0:07:05.24,Default,,0,0,0,,If the mainland becomes a battlefield, \Nall elderly, children, and weak will be massacred.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.74,0:07:10.19,Default,,0,0,0,,"I won't be fussing over those \Nwho may start burdening me in the future." {lit: myself from now on become impediment; burden; encumbrance; hindrance; drag people, cannot do shinju with - shinyu could be "invasion; incursion; raid; aggression; intrusion; trespass; penetration; hacking" (doubt it), or "group suicide" (doubt even more), assumed he means "if the wear, elderly etc are such a hindrance, then begone with them"}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.19,0:07:12.82,Default,,0,0,0,,I heard one of our general say that.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.82,0:07:13.79,Default,,0,0,0,,What?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:14.68,0:07:17.65,Default,,0,0,0,,They intend to massacre their own people?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.22,0:07:19.91,Default,,0,0,0,,What are they even thinking? {cant hear, kinda like "what an unthinkable thing to say"}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:22.80,0:07:28.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Thus, innocent people were squeezed between a rock and a hard place, where both friend and foe wanted them dead.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:28.95,0:07:33.52,Default,,0,0,0,,And as if to follow through with that decision, \None more calamity would befall them.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.02,0:07:38.79,Default,,0,0,0,,At 8:15 a.m. on August 6th, 1945,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.29,0:07:41.92,Default,,0,0,0,,for the first time in human history,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:42.37,0:07:45.42,Default,,0,0,0,,an atomic sun dawned upon Hiroshima. {unsure whats hirameita here, could be "people of ... were blinded/dazzled by atomic bomb" could be "was dropped on ..."}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:45.88,0:07:52.47,Default,,0,0,0,,In an instant, 240,000 people \Nperished or were injured here.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.47,0:08:00.02,Default,,0,0,0,,But it did not end there, as on August 9th, around 11:00 a.m. a plutonium bomb was also dropped on Nagasaki.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.02,0:08:03.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Here, another 100,000 people
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.52,0:08:05.86,Default,,0,0,0,,perished in an instant.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.69,0:08:13.61,Default,,0,0,0,,But what surprised the Japanese high command the most \Nwas the sudden declaration of war by the Soviet Union,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:13.61,0:08:17.81,Default,,0,0,0,,whom they previously tried to get \Nto mediate peace between Japan and the Allies.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:30.13,0:08:36.01,Default,,0,0,0,,At 14:30 on August 9th, \Nthe first of a series of cabinet meetings was held. {not sure what to make of "first round": 14時半より第一回の閣議が開催された}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.59,0:08:42.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Once Foreign Minister Togo finished explaining his position, \NPrime Minister Suzuki Kantaro stood up. {nc what's genkyuu}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.98,0:08:49.69,Default,,0,0,0,,As could be inferred from Minister Togo's presentation, \Nthese are truly desperate times now.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:50.28,0:08:55.45,Default,,0,0,0,,I would like everyone of you to put forward all the questions and opinions you have.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.45,0:09:01.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Our goal today is to determine our course of action \Nin regard to the trilateral declaration.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.37,0:09:06.21,Default,,0,0,0,,At present, no matter how much the three countries talk about the safely of the Imperial Family,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.21,0:09:08.51,Default,,0,0,0,,and what favorable conditions they offer,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:08.51,0:09:11.25,Default,,0,0,0,,unconditional surrender is unacceptable. {/unbearable}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.25,0:09:13.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, with the atomic bombings
Dialogue: 0,0:09:13.97,0:09:15.48,Default,,0,0,0,,and Soviet entry into the war,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.09,0:09:19.55,Default,,0,0,0,,if we look at it with a cool head, \Nwe have no prospects of victory. {mercenary; calculative; greedy; commercial-minded; venal​}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.55,0:09:26.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, if we want to preserve the honor of the Yamato people, \Nwe should look for some opening while we keep fighting.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.14,0:09:32.68,Default,,0,0,0,,If we go on the warpath of seeking to win with our backs to the wall, we won't necessarily face utter destruction, {/in our fatal situation}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:33.32,0:09:37.86,Default,,0,0,0,,but instead, the situation \Non the battlefield may turn to our favor.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.86,0:09:40.81,Default,,0,0,0,,The basis for the existence of that chance being...? {lit: is there something concrete to that chance?}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.45,0:09:43.31,Default,,0,0,0,,A decisive battle on the mainland!
Dialogue: 0,0:09:46.32,0:09:50.17,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm sure, that's where we'll get our chance!
Dialogue: 0,0:09:50.17,0:09:52.32,Default,,0,0,0,,It's where our army would prove its worth! {/show them the power of ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:52.32,0:09:58.88,Default,,0,0,0,,No, given the current realities of warfare, you can't do any fighting without mobilizing the entire nation's effort for it.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:58.88,0:10:04.20,Default,,0,0,0,,In war, you don't send the army and the navy \Nto fight each on their own.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.20,0:10:09.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Even before the atomic bombing and the Soviet entry into the war,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:09.19,0:10:16.82,Default,,0,0,0,,the material situation on the homefront was already desperate, not allowing for any continuation of the war.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:16.82,0:10:22.15,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, if we look at our navy, it stands no chance \Nof scoring any victory on the US or the UK.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:22.15,0:10:25.43,Default,,0,0,0,,This is not the time to be particular about honor.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.43,0:10:28.97,Default,,0,0,0,,I think it's about time we left the sour grapes \Nand wishful thinking behind,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:28.97,0:10:32.61,Default,,0,0,0,,and switched to a discussion \Nfrom a realistic point of view.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:33.80,0:10:38.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Thus, the cabinet was split on those who advocated accepting the joint trilateral declaration,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.88,0:10:42.55,Default,,0,0,0,,like Foreign Minister Togo \Nor Minister of the Navy Yonai on one side,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:42.55,0:10:46.58,Default,,0,0,0,,and Minister of War Anami \Nwith Minister of Munitions Toyoda in the opposition.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:46.58,0:10:51.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Going back and forth, the hot debate \Nwas being fought until after 22:00.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:51.67,0:10:56.15,Default,,0,0,0,,However, even that was ultimately inconclusive.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:02.38,0:11:05.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what conclusion did the cabinet arrive at?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:05.54,0:11:08.18,Default,,0,0,0,,No, no conclusion was achieved yet.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.58,0:11:11.98,Default,,0,0,0,,By the way, chief, \Nwhat is your own stance on it? {/president/head of secret service}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:11.98,0:11:14.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Should we accept it? \NShould we refuse?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:15.96,0:11:17.07,Default,,0,0,0,,As for myself...
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.58,0:11:20.38,Default,,0,0,0,,No.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:21.43,0:11:24.03,Default,,0,0,0,,I may have my own thoughts on that matter.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.50,0:11:28.31,Default,,0,0,0,,But I'm also the cabinet's spokesman.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:28.31,0:11:32.48,Default,,0,0,0,,My duty is to only inform you \Nof the cabinet's collective opinion.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:33.48,0:11:34.65,Default,,0,0,0,,More importantly...
Dialogue: 0,0:11:35.48,0:11:42.48,Default,,0,0,0,,On my way here, I learned something by looking at the sago palm in the garden, adjoining the prime minister's residence.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:42.48,0:11:45.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah. That big sago palm, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:46.98,0:11:52.62,Default,,0,0,0,,As expected, both the trees and the leaves \Nwere burned to the ground in one of the air raids.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:53.75,0:11:55.57,Default,,0,0,0,,But when I looked at it today,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.13,0:11:58.71,Default,,0,0,0,,amidst those scorched trunks,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:59.17,0:12:01.99,Default,,0,0,0,,I noticed some new green shoots sprouting.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:03.49,0:12:06.01,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese people are the sago palm.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:06.68,0:12:10.13,Default,,0,0,0,,No matter what befalls them, \None day, new shoots will bloom.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:10.48,0:12:12.29,Default,,0,0,0,,We can't let the root rot set in!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:12.78,0:12:15.26,Default,,0,0,0,,They have to survive, in some form or another.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:18.65,0:12:20.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. Yes, I'll go there at once.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:21.26,0:12:22.01,Default,,0,0,0,,What is it?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:22.57,0:12:27.51,Default,,0,0,0,,At 23:50, the supreme war committee would assemble. {lit: War Leaders’ Meeting }
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.99,0:12:29.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Eh? This late?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:30.75,0:12:31.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:32.12,0:12:33.29,Default,,0,0,0,,For a little longer,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:33.29,0:12:35.69,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll have to to keep watering those shoots. {lit: NOT to let dry; to kill (vegetation); to season (lumber)}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:35.69,0:12:36.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Where, sir?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:38.44,0:12:39.70,Default,,0,0,0,,In the palace.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:40.17,0:12:42.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Palace? Which means, it's an Imperial Council? {Gozen Kaigi​(literally the conference before the noble face) was an extraconstitutional conference of matters of grave national importance in foreign affairs that were convened by the government of the Empire of Japan in the presence of the Emperor.}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.80,0:12:49.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Look, we have the sago palm here as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:01.38,0:13:06.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Thus, at 23:50 on August 9th,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:06.41,0:13:12.69,Default,,0,0,0,,an Imperial Council was convened, petitioning the Emperor \Nto pass a decision and issue an Imperial Decree.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.71,0:13:18.28,Default,,0,0,0,,The various ministers awaiting the supreme conference were a motley crew.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.28,0:13:22.45,Default,,0,0,0,,But their thoughts were universally directed \Nat the outcome of the Imperial Council.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:27.06,0:13:30.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Shimomura, may I ask something?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:31.31,0:13:36.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Has someone petitioned His Majesty \Nfor an Imperial Decree like that ever before?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:36.06,0:13:37.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Never.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:37.81,0:13:40.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Up until now, even if it was called an Imperial Decree,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:40.40,0:13:44.61,Default,,0,0,0,,it was in fact just a summarized opinion \Nof His vassals that His Majesty would authorize.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:45.05,0:13:50.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Never before has His Majesty been forced \Nto make a decision Himself, like in the current case.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.40,0:13:51.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Things are truly grim for us. {lit: it's a very scary thing}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.98,0:13:53.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Hmm. So I thought.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:53.20,0:13:54.97,Default,,0,0,0,,This is unprecedented.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:56.14,0:14:00.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Trying to rectify the chain of previous \Nbad decisions must be painful for Him. {lit: It must be painful for Him, with the decisions made to lead us here}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.16,0:14:11.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Aren't stars beautiful?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:12.02,0:14:15.81,Default,,0,0,0,,When you visited the palace the other day, \Nwhat was it you told them? {unsure why he says konoaida since this is supposed to be his first visit to the palace and he said he only thought of the sago palm analogy today and he told it in intel. bureau, not in palace so idk}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:15.81,0:14:17.84,Default,,0,0,0,,About sago palms.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.84,0:14:21.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh? So it was you who launched that anecdote? {no clue again: the other day, you told this story}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:21.00,0:14:25.02,Default,,0,0,0,,That time, I told them that no matter \Nwhat happens to the old leaves,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:25.02,0:14:30.02,Default,,0,0,0,,as long as the roots haven't withered, \Nnew shoots will always sprout.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:32.18,0:14:35.02,Default,,0,0,0,,"No matter what happens to the old leaves?"
Dialogue: 0,0:14:38.09,0:14:39.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you for waiting.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:39.62,0:14:43.07,Default,,0,0,0,,The Supreme War Council is now over.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:43.52,0:14:46.85,Default,,0,0,0,,A cabinet meeting will now be held in the conference room.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:59.98,0:15:04.30,Default,,0,0,0,,We will now voice our opinions, one by one.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:05.13,0:15:08.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Once that is done, an Imperial Decree will be issued.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:11.60,0:15:13.52,Default,,0,0,0,,The gist of what He said is,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:14.70,0:15:19.78,Default,,0,0,0,,"when we look at the actual state of the nation, \Nit is evident that prolonging the war any further {unsure why he says "nations; states"}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:20.56,0:15:23.16,Default,,0,0,0,,will not only lead to the destruction of Japan,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:23.86,0:15:27.71,Default,,0,0,0,,but would also knock humanity as a whole \Nback into the middle ages. {lit: trick humanity of the world into much worse misery}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:28.17,0:15:36.01,Default,,0,0,0,,It's this time when one has to endure the unendurable, suffer the insufferable, and accept the Trilateral Declaration.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:36.01,0:15:39.60,Default,,0,0,0,,If that's the only way to end the war, then so be it." {https://www.nationalww2museum.org/war/articles/japans-surrender-military-coup-1945}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:46.82,0:15:48.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Furthermore, His Majesty
Dialogue: 0,0:15:49.15,0:15:53.24,Default,,0,0,0,,expressed sympathy for soldiers \Nfrom the Army and Navy alike, alive or dead,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:53.24,0:15:57.59,Default,,0,0,0,,as well as to everyone else \Nwho had somehow suffered from this war.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:58.12,0:16:00.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Thus, the decree was passed.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:00.85,0:16:07.75,Default,,0,0,0,,However, in some parts of the Army and Navy, the opposition was still vocal on the question of conditions,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.75,0:16:13.16,Default,,0,0,0,,under which the Trilateral Declaration would be accepted.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.77,0:16:20.52,Default,,0,0,0,,And so, on the 14th, another Imperial Council was convened, with all the ministers attending.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:20.52,0:16:25.21,Default,,0,0,0,,There, at last, it was decided \Nthat they'd accept the unconditional surrender.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:38.62,0:16:42.35,Default,,0,0,0,,I apologize for the last time. \NIs this the draft for an Imperial Edict?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:42.87,0:16:43.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:43.83,0:16:46.56,Default,,0,0,0,,When the time comes to publish this decision,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:46.56,0:16:52.46,Default,,0,0,0,,I need to somehow get even the common people to understand it clearly, which is somewhat tricky.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:52.46,0:16:55.58,Default,,0,0,0,,And which medium do you plan to use to announce it?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:55.58,0:16:57.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Newspapers and radio.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:57.93,0:17:01.54,Default,,0,0,0,,I've arranged things with both. \NYou can leave everything to me. {no clue what he means by 一人ということになってね assumed ichinin to be "entrusting (everything to); leaving (a matter) entirely with"}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:02.16,0:17:03.54,Default,,0,0,0,,There's a problem with that.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:04.23,0:17:05.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Did something happen?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:05.46,0:17:07.10,Default,,0,0,0,,A Jewel Voice Broadcast, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:07.10,0:17:07.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:07.91,0:17:11.48,Default,,0,0,0,,I just learned that a portion of the officers \Nare trying to thwart it.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.03,0:17:14.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh? Thank you for letting me know.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:14.47,0:17:16.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Please take some countermeasures.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.47,0:17:19.74,Default,,0,0,0,,No countermeasure is needed.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:20.64,0:17:23.12,Default,,0,0,0,,His Majesty's life depends on this decree,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:23.87,0:17:26.48,Default,,0,0,0,,so I will also protect it with my life.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:31.92,0:17:38.20,Default,,0,0,0,,The other day, when I received \NHis Majesty's decree, I pondered deeply.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.53,0:17:44.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Because it's His final decision, \Nit's a matter of life and death.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:44.29,0:17:48.85,Default,,0,0,0,,So until the final judgment is passed, \Nthere ought to be some turbulence along the way. {lit: various noise/interference/criticism will enter}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:49.92,0:17:54.32,Default,,0,0,0,,When your life is at stake, you tend to make decisions \Nthat deviate from your true intentions. {lit: can always make a decision that changes your ... - I think he compares the emp. to officers, meaning their decision is to reject the potsdam because they know they'll be court-martial'd}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.69,0:17:57.38,Default,,0,0,0,,I myself also contributed to that turbulence.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:57.38,0:18:02.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, but everyone else came to think \Nthey're doing it for the good of the nation.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:02.16,0:18:06.81,Default,,0,0,0,,However, there are more ways than one \Nto do something for the good of the nation.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:07.83,0:18:12.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Make no mistake, though - \Nthis decision is for the supreme commander to make.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:12.69,0:18:19.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Is that to say, your current life-threatening assignment is to pass His Majesty's words to the people whatever it takes?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:19.53,0:18:20.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:23.76,0:18:27.64,Default,,0,0,0,,At 10:00 a.m. on August 14th,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:27.64,0:18:32.73,Default,,0,0,0,,an unprecedented recording in Japanese history was made, the "Jewel Voice Broadcast."
Dialogue: 0,0:18:49.02,0:18:50.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Yabe,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:51.08,0:18:52.54,Default,,0,0,0,,is it correct that you and me
Dialogue: 0,0:18:52.54,0:18:57.46,Default,,0,0,0,,are the only ones who know that the recording was placed \Nin a safe in the Ministry of the Imperial Household?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:57.46,0:18:58.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:58.03,0:19:00.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Someone might try to arrest us tonight.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:00.56,0:19:01.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Huh?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:01.03,0:19:05.02,Default,,0,0,0,,I won't tell them anything, \Neven if it will cost me my life.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:05.02,0:19:07.04,Default,,0,0,0,,I want you to keep silent too.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:07.04,0:19:08.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Certainly, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:14.11,0:19:15.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Cabinet Minister Shimomura?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:15.82,0:19:16.55,Default,,0,0,0,,That is me.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:16.55,0:19:17.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:17.99,0:19:19.10,Default,,0,0,0,,take him to the place.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:37.34,0:19:38.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Shimomura Hiroshi?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:40.09,0:19:41.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Come with me for a moment.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:02.86,0:20:04.71,Default,,0,0,0,,I brought Shimomura Hiroshi, sir!
Dialogue: 0,0:20:04.71,0:20:05.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Well done.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:06.08,0:20:09.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you the head of the intelligence bureau \NShimomura Hiroshi?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:09.40,0:20:10.39,Default,,0,0,0,,That is correct.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:10.39,0:20:15.06,Default,,0,0,0,,We have searched the car just now. \N The Jewel Voice recording is not here.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:15.06,0:20:16.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Where did you hide it?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:16.40,0:20:20.41,Default,,0,0,0,,What do you gentlemen want that record for?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:20.92,0:20:22.91,Default,,0,0,0,,I want to bide our time for a couple days more.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:22.91,0:20:26.70,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll use that time to convince His Majesty \Nthat the military can be trusted.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:26.70,0:20:29.41,Default,,0,0,0,,You think you can do it in just a couple of days?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.41,0:20:33.13,Default,,0,0,0,,That is for me to handle! \NJust tell me where the recording is.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.13,0:20:34.63,Default,,0,0,0,,I can't tell you.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:37.63,0:20:39.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, want us to frisk you? {believing HA}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:39.63,0:20:41.74,Default,,0,0,0,,That was when minister Shimomura
Dialogue: 0,0:20:42.36,0:20:45.87,Default,,0,0,0,,was preparing to face \Nthe tragic consequences of his decision. {nc what he means, was "afraid to die" in HA, lit is "to be immersed in (joy, memories, alcohol, etc.); to give oneself over to; to bask IN THE feeling of tragic heroism; feeling of grim resolve; sense of determination OF putting his life on the line / 命を懸ける悲壮さに浸った "}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:46.85,0:20:48.91,Default,,0,0,0,,But at the same time,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:48.91,0:20:54.52,Default,,0,0,0,,he thought of the mainland defense strategy \Nthat Minister of War Anami bet his life on. {very unsure what means, nc what's junsui (pure; true; genuine; unmixed); was "he envisioned a defensive mainland operation at the behest of the Minister of the Imperial Japanese Army Anan." in HA; 阿波見陸将の命を懸けた純粋の本土作戦を思った}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.79,0:21:00.13,Default,,0,0,0,,"Just because you bet your life on it, \Ndoesn't mean your judgment is correct."
Dialogue: 0,0:21:01.24,0:21:05.57,Default,,0,0,0,,What would be the supreme commander's decision? {no clue: highest grade; finest quality; top class MAN}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:05.57,0:21:06.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Stop it!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:08.04,0:21:10.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Dealing with Shimomura now wouldn't do us any good.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:10.85,0:21:13.59,Default,,0,0,0,,If he won't spill it, search inside the Ministry!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:14.02,0:21:14.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:14.58,0:21:19.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Until our work here is done, \Nherd them all into that room.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:19.16,0:21:20.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay. Roger that.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:23.82,0:21:28.53,Default,,0,0,0,,They walked the NHK Director Yabe \Nthrough all the rooms in the Ministry,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:28.53,0:21:34.11,Default,,0,0,0,,pressing him to reveal the location of the recording. \NBut he kept pretending he doesn't know.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:35.73,0:21:42.50,Default,,0,0,0,,In addition, some of the rebellious officers \Nraided the NHK studios at dawn on the 15th,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:42.50,0:21:46.11,Default,,0,0,0,,desperately trying to get airtime for themselves, but to no avail.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:46.11,0:21:50.02,Default,,0,0,0,,They eventually returned to the Imperial Palace \Nand committed suicide.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:04.01,0:22:08.32,Default,,0,0,0,,{\i1}We have resolved to pave the way, for a grand peace, {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hirohito_surrender_broadcast#Full_text / https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E7%8E%89%E9%9F%B3%E6%94%BE%E9%80%81#%E5%85%A8%E6%96%87}{\i0}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:08.32,0:22:17.60,Default,,0,0,0,,{\i1}for all the generations to come by enduring the unendurable \Nand suffering what is insufferable. {然れども朕は時運の赴く所 堪え難きを堪え 忍び難きを忍び もって万世の為に太平を開かんと欲す}{\i0}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:17.60,0:22:26.86,Default,,0,0,0,,{\i1}Having been able to safeguard and maintain our sovereignty, we are always with you, our good and loyal subjects... {朕はここに国体を護持し得て 忠良なる汝臣民の赤誠に信倚し 常に汝臣民と共に在り}{\i0}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:26.86,0:22:32.87,Default,,0,0,0,,The other day, remember how I told you that the supreme commander's decision is a matter of life and death? {nc, he didn't say that in anime, "highest grade; finest quality; top class" may mean hirohito, or may mean "the final decision"}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:32.87,0:22:35.02,Default,,0,0,0,,That's what I think too.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:35.83,0:22:41.11,Default,,0,0,0,,But now I believe that alone is not enough \Nto attach credibility to your judgment. {/doesn't make it a true decision}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:43.36,0:22:45.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Everyone was betting his life on it.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:46.24,0:22:51.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Starting with His Majesty, to Anami, Yonai, and Togo.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:52.20,0:22:57.56,Default,,0,0,0,,However, why does everyone come to a different conclusion when putting his life on the line?
Dialogue: 0,0:22:59.04,0:23:03.36,Default,,0,0,0,,That difference is the cornerstone of our sovereignty. \NThe spirit of what we call "Japan."
Dialogue: 0,0:23:04.81,0:23:08.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Our country of Japan is really \Nall about the people remaining in it.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:10.68,0:23:13.75,Default,,0,0,0,,They haven't grasped this underlying idea. {root; origin; source; cause; basis; foundation}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:14.26,0:23:17.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Without a country, there can be no sovereignty, no nothing.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:18.35,0:23:22.01,Default,,0,0,0,,And the most important thing now \Nis to leave that country alone. {/let live}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.69,0:23:24.67,Default,,0,0,0,,As long as this country lives,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:25.40,0:23:28.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Japan will surely blossom once again. {/sprout shoots}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:28.14,0:23:30.85,Default,,0,0,0,,And it's up to us to observe those flowers closely. {lit: そのテーマをしっかり見つめる目だ / eyes/shoots that look closely at that theme/topic - nc what he means}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:31.28,0:23:33.60,Default,,0,0,0,,However, in order to see them blossom,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:33.60,0:23:35.95,Default,,0,0,0,,we need to learn to step back. {lit: we can't get stuck in our position - prolly means "someone will rebuild japan but it cant be us/in order to bring it to a bright future, we needed to back down, shove our pride away and end the war"}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:36.39,0:23:39.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Relinquishing your present for the sake of the future {将来の見通しに立つかどうかなんじゃないかな}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:40.08,0:23:42.37,Default,,0,0,0,,is the one true decision.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.63,0:23:45.64,Default,,0,0,0,,And also
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.59,0:23:49.51,Default,,0,0,0,,the most courageous one. {nc what he means: and later - courage}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:57.37,0:24:07.18,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(100,0)}The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace.\NBut also instilled numerous lessons on how to live.{太平洋戦争はわれわれに平和の尊さを教えたがまた生きるための教訓を数多くのこしている}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.70,0:24:17.39,Default,,0,0,50,,If you're a man, let's put your strength to test{男だったら　力を試せ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:17.39,0:24:21.60,Default,,0,0,50,,If you are a man, keep your hopes sizzling{男だったら　希望(のぞみ)を燃やせ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:21.60,0:24:25.82,Default,,0,0,50,,If you are a man, don't lose your heart{男だったら　くじけるな}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:25.82,0:24:34.36,Default,,0,0,50,,Because there's just you and me, a man and a man{俺もおまえも　男と男}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:34.36,0:24:42.77,Default,,0,0,50,,With crimson blood flowing in our veins all the same{おなじ真赤な　血が通う}
